Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for compiling a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <!-- Project Information -->
    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>

    <!-- Project Name and Description -->
    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <!-- Project Properties -->
    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <!-- Project Dependencies -->
    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <!-- Project Build Settings -->
    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>

To support Azure Active Directory (AAD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens in Apache Airflow, you'll need to configure the `auth_backend` and `auth_type` settings in your `airflow.cfg` file.

Here's an example configuration code snippet that you can use as a starting point:
```python
[core]
auth_backend = airflow.contrib.auth.backends.azure_active_directory

[azure_active_directory]
client_id = <your_client_id>
client_secret = <your_client_secret>
tenant_id = <your_tenant_id>
authority = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>
token_endpoint = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>/oauth2/v2.0/token
```
Replace the placeholders with your actual Azure AD application settings:

* `<your_client_id>`: The client ID of your Azure AD application.
* `<your_client_secret>`: The client secret of your Azure AD application.
* `<your_tenant_id>`: The tenant ID of your Azure AD tenant.

You'll also need to install the `azure-identity` and `azure-core` libraries, which are required for Azure AD authentication. You can do this by running the following command:
```
pip install azure-identity azure-core
```

You can use the `zellij` command `:copy` to copy the current pane's scrollback to the system clipboard. Here are the steps:

1. Open `zellij` and navigate to the pane with the scrollback output you want to copy.
2. Press `Ctrl + A` to enter command mode.
3. Type `:copy` and press Enter.
4. The scrollback output will be copied to the system clipboard.

Alternatively, you can use the `zellij` command `:save` to save the scrollback output to a file. Here are the steps:

1. Open `zellij` and navigate to the pane with the scrollback output you want to save.
2. Press `Ctrl + A` to enter command mode.
3. Type `:save <filename>` and press Enter.
4. The scrollback output will be saved to the specified file.

If you want to extract the data programmatically, you can use the `zellij` command `:dump` to dump the scrollback output to a file or pipe it to another command. Here are the steps:

1. Open `zellij` and navigate to the pane with the scrollback output you want to dump.
2. Press `Ctrl + A` to enter command mode.
3. Type `:dump <filename>` and press Enter.
4. The scrollback output will be dumped to the specified file.

You can also use the `zellij` command `:dump -` to pipe the scrollback output to another command. For example:

`:dump - | grep <pattern>`

This will pipe the scrollback output to `grep` and search for the specified pattern.
